description: From Middle English eten, from Old English etan (“to eat”), from Proto-West Germanic *etan, from Proto-Germanic *etaną (“to eat”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁édti, from *h₁ed- (“to eat”).

verbs.description: eat (third-person singular simple present eats, present participle eating, simple past ate or (dialectal) et or (obsolete) eat, past participle eaten or (dialectal) etten)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To consume (something solid or semi-solid, usually food) by putting it into the mouth and swallowing it.
examples: He's eating an apple. / Don't disturb me now; can't you see that I'm eating?
What time do we eat this evening?
It's a soup that eats like a meal.

entries.meaning: (copulative, intransitive) To have a particular quality of diet; to be well-fed or underfed (typically as "eat healthy" or "eat good").
(transitive, often with up) To destroy, consume, or use up.
examples: This project is eating up all the money.

entries.meaning: (transitive, programming, informal) To consume (an exception, an event, etc.) so that other parts of the program do not receive it.
examples: A bigger problem, however, is that if you catch/eat an exception and do nothing with it, you are very likely introducing subtle bugs in your application that will be next to impossible to track down.

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal, of a device) To damage, destroy, or fail to eject a removable part or an inserted object.
examples: The VHS recorder just ate the tape and won't spit it out.
John is late for the meeting because the photocopier ate his report.

entries.meaning: (transitive, informal, of a vending machine or similar device) To consume money (or other instruments of value, such as a token) deposited or inserted by a user, while failing to either provide the intended product or service or return the payment.
examples: The video game in the corner just ate my quarter.

entries.meaning: (transitive, business) To take the loss in a transaction.
examples: I have to have him in court tomorrow, if he doesn't show up, I forfeit the bond and I have to eat the $300,000.

entries.meaning: (transitive, slang) To be injured or killed by (something such as a firearm or its projectile), especially in the mouth.
examples: I risk my whole future, the hatred of the cops and Eddie Mars' gang. I dodge bullets and eat saps.
The acid rain ate away the statue.  The strong acid eats through the metal.

entries.meaning: (transitive, slang) To perform oral sex (on a person or body part).
examples: Yeah, eat that dick / eat that pussy.

entries.meaning: (stative, slang) To be very good; to rule; to rock.

description: From Middle English ete, ate, æte, from Old English ǣt (“food, eating”), from Proto-West Germanic *āt, from Proto-Germanic *ētą (“food, thing to eat”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁ed- (“to eat”). Cognate with North Frisian ad, it (“food”), German Aas (“carrion”), Norwegian åt, Icelandic át (“food”).

entries.meaning: (colloquial) Something to be eaten; a meal; a food item.
examples: Eating a Picnic creates a flurry of wafer pieces, flying peanuts and chocolate crumbs.  […]  As well as being messy, Picnic happens to be a big eat – something of a consumption challenge in fact.
